In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert that a value has a specific type, even if the type system doesn't know that the value will always have that type. This is known as type assertion.

For example:
```
let value: string | number = "hello";

// This will give a warning because the value could also be a number
console.log(value.toUpperCase());

// This will not give a warning because we are asserting that the value is a string
console.log(value.toUpperCase() as string);
```
Alternatively, you can also use `typeof` operator to assert the type
```
console.log(value.toUpperCase() as typeof value);
```
It's important to use type assertions sparingly, as they can make your code less type-safe and can make it harder to catch type-related errors. Use them only when you are certain that the value will always have the specific type you are asserting.

